# type: Content of: <chapter><section><note><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:49
msgid ""
"These instructions assume that you've installed Nagios according to the "
"<link linkend=\"gettingstarted-quickstart\">quickstart guide</link>. The "
"sample configuration entries below reference objects that are defined in the "
"sample config files (<filename>commands.cfg</filename>, <filename>templates."
"cfg</filename>, etc.) that are installed when you follow the quickstart."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:67
msgid ""
"Monitoring switches and routers can either be easy or more involved - "
"depending on what equipment you have and what you want to monitor. As they "
"are critical infrastructure components, you'll no doubt want to monitor them "
"in at least some basic manner."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:72
msgid ""
"Switches and routers can be monitored easily by \"pinging\" them to "
"determine packet loss,"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><application>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:73
msgid ""
", etc. If your switch supports &protocol-snmp;, you can monitor port status, "
"etc. with the &plugin-snmp; plugin and bandwidth (if you're using "
"<application>"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><application><acronym>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:76
msgid "MRTG"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:76
msgid "</application>) with the &plugin-mrtgtraf; plugin."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:79
msgid ""
"The &plugin-snmp; plugin will only get compiled and installed if you have "
"the net-snmp and net-snmp-utils packages installed on your system. Make sure "
"the plugin exists in <filename class=\"directory\">/usr/local/nagios/"
"libexec</filename> before you continue. If it doesn't, install "
"<application>net-snmp</application> and <application>net-snmp-utils</"
"application> and recompile/reinstall the Nagios plugins."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:91
msgid ""
"There are several steps you'll need to follow in order to monitor a new "
"router or switch. They are:"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><procedure><step><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:100
msgid "Create new host and service definitions for monitoring the device"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:118
msgid ""
"Two command definitions (<emphasis>check_snmp</emphasis> and "
"<emphasis>check_local_mrtgtraf</emphasis>) have been added to the "
"<filename>commands.cfg</filename> file. These allows you to use the &plugin-"
"snmp; and &plugin-mrtgtraf; plugins to monitor network routers."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:126
msgid ""
"A switch host template (called <emphasis>generic-switch</emphasis>) has "
"already been created in the <filename>templates.cfg</filename> file. This "
"allows you to add new router/switch host definitions in a simple manner."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:133
msgid ""
"The above-mentioned config files can be found in the <filename class="
"\"directory\">/usr/local/nagios/etc/objects/</filename> directory. You can "
"modify the definitions in these and other definitions to suit your needs "
"better if you'd like. However, I'd recommend waiting until you're more "
"familiar with configuring Nagios before doing so. For the time being, just "
"follow the directions outlined below and you'll be monitoring your network "
"routers/switches in no time."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:145
msgid ""
"The first time you configure Nagios to monitor a network switch, you'll need "
"to do a bit of extra work. Remember, you only need to do this for the "
"*first* switch you monitor."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlisting>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:156
#, no-wrap
msgid "#cfg_file=/usr/local/nagios/etc/objects/switch.cfg"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:160
msgid ""
"What did you just do? You told Nagios to look to the <filename>/usr/local/"
"nagios/etc/objects/switch.cfg</filename> to find additional object "
"definitions. That's where you'll be adding host and service definitions for "
"routers and switches. That configuration file already contains some sample "
"host, hostgroup, and service definitions. For the *first* router/switch you "
"monitor, you can simply modify the sample host and service definitions in "
"that file, rather than creating new ones."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:173
msgid ""
"You'll need to create some <link linkend=\"configuringnagios-"
"objectdefinitions\">object definitions</link> in order to monitor a new "
"router/switch."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:176
msgid "Open the <filename>switch.cfg</filename> file for editing."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><screen>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:178
#, no-wrap
msgid "<prompt>linux:~ # </prompt><userinput>vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/objects/switch.cfg</userinput>"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:180
msgid ""
"Add a new <link linkend=\"configuringnagios-objectdefinitions-host\">host</"
"link> definition for the switch that you're going to monitor. If this is the "
"*first* switch you're monitoring, you can simply modify the sample host "
"definition in <filename>switch.cfg</filename>. Change the "
"<varname>host_name</varname>, <varname>alias</varname>, and "
"<varname>address</varname> fields to appropriate values for the switch."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlisting>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:188
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"define host{\n"
"    use        generic-switch         ; Inherit default values from a template\n"
"    host_name  linksys-srw224p        ; The name we're giving to this switch\n"
"    alias      Linksys SRW224P Switch ; A longer name associated with the switch\n"
"    address    192.168.1.253          ; IP address of the switch\n"
"    hostgroups allhosts,switches      ; Host groups this switch is associated with\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><title>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:200
msgid "Monitoring Services"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:202
msgid ""
"Now you can add some service definitions (to the same configuration file) to "
"monitor different aspects of the switch. If this is the *first* switch "
"you're monitoring, you can simply modify the sample service definition in "
"<filename>switch.cfg</filename>."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><note><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:208
msgid ""
"Replace <quote><replaceable>linksys-srw224p</replaceable></quote> in the "
"example definitions below with the name you specified in the "
"<varname>host_name</varname> directive of the host definition you just added."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><title>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:216
msgid "Monitoring Packet Loss and RTA"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:218
msgid ""
"Add the following service definition in order to monitor packet loss and "
"round trip average between the Nagios host and the switch every 5 minutes "
"under normal conditions."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><programlisting>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:231
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"define service{\n"
"   use                    generic-service\n"
"   host_name              linksys-srw224p\n"
"   service_description    PING\n"
"   check_command          check_ping!200.0,20%!600.0,60%\n"
"   normal_check_interval  5\n"
"   retry_check_interval   1\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><calloutlist><callout><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:243
msgid "Inherit values from a template"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><calloutlist><callout><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:246
msgid "The name of the host the service is associated with"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><calloutlist><callout><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:249
msgid "The service description"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><calloutlist><callout><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:252
msgid "The command used to monitor the service"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><calloutlist><callout><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:255
msgid "Check the service every 5 minutes under normal conditions"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlistingco><calloutlist><callout><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:258
msgid ""
"Re-check the service every minute until its final/hard state is determined"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:264
msgid "This service will be:"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:268
msgid "CRITICAL if the round trip average ("
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:268
msgid ") is greater than 600 milliseconds or the packet loss is 60% or more"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:273
msgid "WARNING if the"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:273
msgid "is greater than 200 ms or the packet loss is 20% or more"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:278
msgid "OK if the"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:278
msgid "is less than 200 ms and the packet loss is less than 20%"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><title>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:285
msgid "Monitoring SNMP Status Information"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:287
msgid ""
"If your switch or router supports &protocol-snmp;, you can monitor a lot of "
"information by using the &plugin-snmp; plugin. If it doesn't, skip this "
"section."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:291
msgid ""
"Add the following service definition to monitor the uptime of the switch."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlisting>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:294
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"define service{\n"
"    use                  generic-service ; Inherit values from a template\n"
"    host_name            linksys-srw224p\n"
"    service_description  Uptime\n"
"    check_command        check_snmp!-C public -o sysUpTime.0\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:303
msgid ""
"In the <varname>check_command</varname> directive of the service definition "
"above, the"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><option>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:304
msgid "-C public"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:304
msgid ""
"tells the plugin that the &protocol-snmp; community name to be used is "
"<varname>public</varname> and the <computeroutput>-o sysUpTime.0</"
"computeroutput> indicates which"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><tip><para><acronym>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:307
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:324
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:343
msgid "OID"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:307
msgid "should be checked."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:310
msgid ""
"If you want to ensure that a specific port/interface on the switch is in an "
"up state, you could add a service definition like this:"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlisting>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:313
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"define service{\n"
"    use                 generic-service ; Inherit values from a template\n"
"    host_name           linksys-srw224p\n"
"    service_description Port 1 Link Status\n"
"    check_command       check_snmp!-C public -o ifOperStatus.1 -r 1 -m RFC1213-MIB\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:323
msgid ""
"In the example above, the <computeroutput>-o ifOperStatus.1</computeroutput> "
"refers to the"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:324
msgid "for the operational status of port 1 on the switch."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:327
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:332
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:382
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:387 TheBasics/macros.xml:171
msgid "The"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><option>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:327
msgid "-r 1"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:327
msgid ""
"option tells the &plugin-snmp; plugin to return an OK state if "
"<computeroutput>1</computeroutput> is found in the &protocol-snmp; result (1 "
"indicates an \"up\" state on the port) and CRITICAL if it isn't found."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><option>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:332
msgid "-m RFC1213-MIB"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:332
msgid ""
"is optional and tells the &plugin-snmp; plugin to only load the "
"<quote>RFC1213-MIB</quote> instead of every single"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><acronym>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:334
msgid "MIB"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:334
msgid "that's installed on your system, which can help speed things up."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:337
msgid ""
"That's it for the &protocol-snmp; monitoring example. There are a million "
"things that can be monitored via &protocol-snmp;, so its up to you to decide "
"what you need and want to monitor. Good luck!"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><tip><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:343
msgid "You can usually find the"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><tip><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:343
msgid ""
"s that can be monitored on a switch by running the following command "
"(replace <emphasis>192.168.1.253</emphasis> with the IP address of the "
"switch): <command>snmpwalk -v1 -c public 192.168.1.253 -m ALL .1</command>"
