# type: Content of: <chapter><section><title>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:351
msgid "Monitoring Bandwidth / Traffic Rate"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:353
msgid ""
"If you're monitoring bandwidth usage on your switches or routers using "
"<ulink url=\"http://oss.oetiker.ch/mrtg/\"><application>MRTG</application></"
"ulink>, you can have Nagios alert you when traffic rates exceed thresholds "
"you specify. The &plugin-mrtgtraf; plugin (which is included in the Nagios "
"plugins distribution) allows you to do this."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:359
msgid ""
"You'll need to let the &plugin-mrtgtraf; plugin know what log file the "
"<application>MRTG</application> data is being stored in, along with "
"thresholds, etc. In my example, I'm monitoring one of the ports on a Linksys "
"switch. The <application>MRTG</application> log file is stored in <filename>/"
"var/lib/mrtg/192.168.1.253_1.log</filename>. Here's the service definition I "
"use to monitor the bandwidth data that's stored in the log file..."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><programlisting>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:368
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"define service{\n"
"   use                 generic-service ; Inherit values from a template\n"
"   host_name           linksys-srw224p\n"
"   service_description Port 1 Bandwidth Usage\n"
"   check_command       check_local_mrtgtraf!/var/lib/mrtg/192.168.1.253_1.log!AVG!1000000,2000000!5000000,5000000!10\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:377
msgid ""
"In the example above, the <filename>/var/lib/mrtg/192.168.1.253_1.log</"
"filename> option that gets passed to the <emphasis>check_local_mrtgtraf</"
"emphasis> command tells the plugin which <application>MRTG</application> log "
"file to read from."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><acronym>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:382
msgid "AVG"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:382
msgid "option tells it that it should use average bandwidth statistics. The"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><option>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:383
msgid "1000000,2000000"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:384
msgid ""
"options are the warning thresholds (in bytes) for incoming traffic rates."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para><option>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:387
msgid "5000000,5000000"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:387
msgid "are critical thresholds (in bytes)  for outgoing traffic rates. The"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><informaltable><tgroup><tbody><row><entry><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:388 TheBasics/statetypes.xml:350
msgid "10"
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:388
msgid ""
"option causes the plugin to return a CRITICAL state if the "
"<application>MRTG</application> log file is older than 10 minutes (it should "
"be updated every 5 minutes)."
msgstr ""

# type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: GettingStarted/monitoring-routers.xml:399
msgid ""
"Once you've added the new host and service definitions to the "
"<filename>switch.cfg</filename> file, you're ready to start monitoring the "
"router/switch. To do this, you'll need to <link linkend=\"runningnagios-"
"verifyconfig\">verify your configuration</link> and <link linkend="
"\"runningnagios-startstop\">restart Nagios</link>."
msgstr ""
